data.chText: （道路、桥梁的）通行费
data.enText: money that you pay to use a particular road or bridge

data.chText: 高速公路通行费
data.enText: motorway tolls

data.chText: 收费道路 / 桥梁
data.enText: a toll road/bridge

data.chText: （战争、灾难等造成的）毁坏；伤亡人数
data.enText: the amount of damage or the number of deaths and injuries that are caused in a particular war, disaster, etc.

data.chText: 官方公布的死亡人数现已达7 000人。
data.enText: The official death toll has now reached 7 000.

data.chText: 不断增长的战争伤亡人数
data.enText: the war's growing casualty toll

data.chText: （缓慢而有规律的）钟声
data.enText: the sound of a bell ringing with slow regular strokes

data.chText: 长途电话费
data.enText: a charge for a telephone call that is calculated at a higher rate than a local call
take a heavy toll (on sb/sth)
take its toll (on sb/sth)

data.chText: 产生恶果；造成重大损失（或伤亡、灾难等）
data.enText: to have a bad effect on sb/sth; to cause a lot of damage, deaths, suffering, etc.

data.chText: 疾病对她的身体造成极大的损害。
data.enText: Illness had taken a heavy toll on her.

data.chText: 经济衰退使住房市场遭受着重大损失。
data.enText: The recession is taking its toll on the housing markets.

data.chText: （缓慢而有规律地）敲（钟）；（尤指）鸣（丧钟）
data.enText: when a bell tolls or sb tolls it, it is rung slowly many times, especially as a sign that sb has died

data.chText: 大教堂为战争中的死难者鸣钟。
data.enText: The Abbey bell tolled for those killed in the war.

data.chText: 鸣钟报时。
data.enText: The bell tolled the hour.

data.chText: 那场革命敲响了俄国君主制的丧钟。
data.enText: The revolution tolled the death knell (= signalled the end) for the Russian monarchy.

data.text: rate ♦ charge ♦ fee ♦ rent ♦ dues ♦ toll ♦ rental ♦ tariff

data.chText: 以上各词均指所收取或付出的费用。
data.enText: These are all words for an amount of money that is charged or paid for sth.
rate

data.chText: 指所索取或付出的价格、费用：
data.enText: a fixed amount of money that is asked or paid for sth

data.chText: 按小时支付的低报酬
data.enText: a low hourly rate of pay

data.chText: 利率
data.enText: interest rates
charge

data.chText: 指商品或服务的要价、收费：
data.enText: an amount of money that is asked for goods or services

data.chText: 入场费
data.enText: an admission charge
fee

data.chText: 指专业服务费、咨询费、学费、会费：
data.enText: ( rather formal ) an amount of money that you have to pay for professional advice or services, to go to a school or college, or to join an organization

data.chText: 诉讼费
data.enText: legal fees

data.chText: 年度会员费
data.enText: an annual membership fee
rent

data.chText: 指房屋租金。
data.enText: an amount of money that you regularly have to pay for use of a building or room

data.chText: 在美国英语中，rent可用以表示rental（租金）：
data.enText: In American English, rent can be used to mean rental .

data.chText: 这辆汽车每周的租金是200多元。
data.enText: The weekly rent on the car was over $200.
dues

data.chText: 指应缴会员费
data.enText: an amount of money that you have to pay so that you can be a member of an organization
toll

data.chText: 指道路、桥梁的通行费
data.enText: an amount of money that you have to pay to use a particular road or bridge
rental

data.chText: 指租金
data.enText: an amount of money that you have to pay to use sth for a particular period of time

data.chText: 用rent还是rental？
在英国英语中，rent只指房屋租金，其他物品的租金用rental。在美国英语中，rent可指以上两种租金，但指其他物品的租金，rental仍然较通用。
data.enText: In British English rent is only money paid to use a building or room: for other items use rental . In American English rent can be used for both, but rental is still more common for other items.
rent or rental?
tariff

data.chText: 指旅馆、餐馆或公司的服务价目表、收费表
data.enText: ( rather formal ) a list of fixed prices that are charged by a hotel or restaurant for rooms or meals, or by a company for a particular service

tr: value measured by what must be given or done or undergone to obtain something
example: the cost in human life was enormous
the price of success is hard work

tr: the sound of a bell being struck
example: she heard the distant toll of church bells

tr: a fee levied for the use of roads or bridges (used for maintenance)

example: Toll the bridges into New York City

value.def: When a bell tolls or when someone tolls it, it rings slowly and repeatedly, often as a sign that someone has died.

example.ex: Church bells tolled and black flags fluttered...
example.tran: 教堂丧钟敲响，黑色的旗帜飘动。

value.tran: (缓慢反复地)敲(钟)，鸣(丧钟);(钟)鸣响

value.def: A toll is a small sum of money that you have to pay in order to use a particular bridge or road.
A toll road or toll bridge is a road or bridge where you have to pay in order to use it.
A toll is a total number of deaths, accidents, or disasters that occur in a particular period of time.

example.ex: There are fears that the casualty toll may be higher.
example.tran: 有人担心伤亡总数可能会更高。

example.ex: …the second highest annual murder toll in that city's history.
example.tran: 年谋杀案件总数处于该市历史上的第二高位

value.def: If you say that something takes its toll or takes a heavy toll, you mean that it has a bad effect or causes a lot of suffering.

example.ex: Winter takes its toll on your health...
Higher fuel prices took their toll.
…a high exchange rate took a heavy toll on industry.
example.tran: 高汇率使工业蒙受了严重损失。

value.tran: 造成恶果(或不利影响、痛苦等)

trans: (事故、战争、灾难等的)死亡人数
(道路上的)收费站，收费区，收费广场
